cles from Latin, Byzantine, and Ottoman perspectives. They also confront readers with the difficulties of interpretation: the production and resonance of crusade propaganda, the complex nature of "eyewitness" sources, and the long-term process that transforms narrative and text into cultural memory. The book also includes an accessible introduction, timelines, and maps. Illuminating the many complexities of late medieval military, diplomatic, and cultural history, The Crusade of 1456 provides access to one of the most interesting yet neglected stories in the history of the crusades.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh  a1456.  aByzantine.  aConstantinople.  aCrusades.  aJohn Hunyadi.  aJohn of Capistrano.  aOttoman Empire.  aSiege of Belgrade.  aSultan Mehmed II.  aTurkish army.  amedieval history.  amilitary history.  aprimary sources in translation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753262840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487532628423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487532628/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles